featured_reviews.review_id: The jama masjid of Gorakhnath, built during the Mughal era, is a stunning and historic mosque with a rich history dating back over 350 years. The mosque underwent renovations 6 years ago, but its original structure remains, including the iconic dome adorned with intricate Persian artwork. With a capacity for 400 worshippers at its time, the mosque has since been expanded to accommodate to accommodate the growing community, with nine entrances and two large minarets that allow for ample ventilation. During regular days, around 2500 worshippers come to their prayers, while during special occasions such as Eid, Bakreed, and Alvida, the number swells to 5000. A must visit for those interested in history and architecture, this mosque truly stands as a testament to the grandeur of the Mughal Era.

This colossal building of mosque lies in epicenter of the city connected with frequent places like bus stand and railway station, accessible by 24 cross 7 transport facilities.
The mosque is named after the renowned physician, social worker and Islamic scholar Hakeem Wasi Ahmad Alig.
Apart from the basic facilities like ablution (wadhu)area, fresh drinking water, washrooms, rest rooms in the premises. The mosque also accommodate a islamic school(Madarsa) and Darul ifta inside the building. The Islamic school(Madarsa) has strength of more than hundreds of students coming from different backgrounds to learn and memorize The Holy Quran.It also imparts basic Arabic and Urdu language understanding to students attending it.Besides ,The Darul Ifta, a consultative and authoritative body of Islamic Laws, offers help to masses in the matters pertaining to the Islamic rules and laws, and also educate them about the same.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Imambara is 'Dargah' (Islamic shrine built over the grave of a religious figure) of the revered Muslim saint, Roshan Ali Shah. It was built in the 17th century and is about two km from the Gorakhpur Railway Station. As beautiful as it should be, the Imambara stands as a pristine white limestone structure to honor the Sufi saint who gave so much to the world in form of his life philosophies and words of wisdom. Do you know that this Dargah is known to preserve a continuous smoke fire? It is called 'dhunj'.It is also famous for its gold and silver 'tazia'. A tazia is a replica tomb of Husain, the martyred son of Muhammad. It is carried in processions and plays mainly during the festival of Shia Muharrum. Devotes from different places visit the Imambara to honor the deceased saint and seek his blessings. Mulsims may visit the shrine for 'ziyarat' (Arabic term for 'visit') that is, for religious visits and pilgrimages. Not only Muslims, the shrine is held in high esteem by people of all faiths who regularly visit the Dargah to offers prayers and light little clay lamps. If you are lucky, you may as well get to hear the musical offerings in form of 'Qawwali' and 'kafi'.

Weather: Summer 20degC to 39degC Winter 10degC to 22degC
